  "time_ut": 1656134012,
  "original_lang": "si",
  "original_title": "\u0da2\u0dcf\u0dad\u0dca\u200d\u0dba\u0db1\u0dca\u0dad\u0dbb \u0d9c\u0db1\u0dd4\u0daf\u0dd9\u0db1\u0dd4 \u0dc0\u0dcf\u0dbb\u0dca\u0dad\u0dcf \u0d9a\u0dbb\u0dab \u0db4\u0daf\u0dca\u0db0\u0dad\u0dd2\u0dba \u0dc4\u0db3\u0dd4\u0db1\u0dca\u0dc0\u0dcf \u0daf\u0dd9\u0dba\u0dd2",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Introduces International Transaction Reporting System",
      "author": "unknown",
      "body_lines": [
        "Recognizing the need to implement a monitoring system for international transactions and domestic foreign currency transactions through the banking system, the Central Bank of Sri Lanka has implemented a new data collection system called the International Transaction Reporting System with the participation of licensed commercial banks and licensed specialized banks.",
        "The Central Bank says that the International Transaction Reporting System is a system for collecting detailed data on cross-border transactions and local foreign currency transactions, and this will help to fill many gaps in the existing data. It will also help policy making by providing multi-faceted data for statistical and regulatory purposes. The International Transaction Reporting System serves a number of purposes including export earnings, imports, outsourcing of IT-based business processes, service account transactions, remittances of foreign employees, balance of payments statistics including financial account transactions and many other statistical data inputs. will perform. The International Transaction Reporting System can also serve the purpose of reporting data by banks for regulatory purposes. International Transaction Reporting System data also contribute to obtaining information regarding the sources of foreign exchange flows from the country for education, medical, tourism and other purposes that help in future policy decisions. The International Transaction Reporting System will also centralize the central bank's information collection, facilitating data reporting by banks. The first phase of the International Transaction Reporting System will go live from June 21, 2022. In the next phases of this system project, it is also expected to centralize and facilitate data reporting of the central bank.",
        "All banks shall report information related to the transactions related to the first phase of the project as per the guidelines related to the International Transaction Reporting System through the website of the International Transaction Reporting System developed by the Central Bank. The Monitoring Unit of the International Transaction Reporting System established within the Central Bank of Sri Lanka will work closely with the banks on a daily basis to ensure the accuracy, timeliness and coverage of the data being reported.",
        "These reporting requirements are based on the powers conferred by the Currency Act No. 58 of 1949, the Banking Act No. 30 of 1988 and the Foreign Exchange Act No. 12 of 2017."
      ],
